Looking at this again, I notice that when you set up diceBound and sourceRec in the constructor, you're using position values before properly initializing them. Let's try restructuring your constructor with an initialization list to ensure all members are properly initialized:

```cpp
Dice::Dice(const char* texturePath, Vector2 pos) 
    : position(pos)
    , diceThrowState(6)
    , NUM_FRAMES(6)
    , isMouseHeld(false)
    , mousePoint{0.0f, 0.0f}
    , texture{0}
{
    texture = LoadTexture(texturePath);
    if (texture.id == 0) {
        std::cerr << "Failed to load texture: " << texturePath << std::endl;
        return;
    }

    frameHeight = (float)texture.height/NUM_FRAMES;

    // Now set up the rectangles after all other members are initialized
    sourceRec = {0, 0, (float)texture.width, frameHeight};
    diceBound = {position.x, position.y, (float)texture.width, frameHeight};
}
```

Also, could you share the code where you're creating and using the Dice object? The segfault might be happening due to how the object is being created or accessed.

If this doesn't help, try adding more debug prints throughout your code to see exactly where it's crashing:

```cpp
